(4137, 663, 'project_description', 'Our preservation approach focuses on the importance of a holistic design that continues the spirit of the original architecture. Over the past 85 years the original Bay Head Yacht Club has been expanded by the accretion of multiple layers and extensions, some that contribute to the meaning and significance of the historic clubhouse and some that obscure it. We began the design process by examining the historic building and creating a chronological study of the changes over time. Our research showed that open porches on the north and south were enclosed and extended, that another porch was added to circumscribe the whole building, and that a series of four additions were added to the east and one to the west of the building. It was determined that the significance of the building lay in the original core building and the layers of enclosed decks that established the character of the north and south elevations of the central portion of the clubhouse. The later fragmented additions tacked onto the east end of the building detract from the original form of the building and were of poor craftsmanship relative to the richness in design of the original construction. In fact, super storm Sandy served to highlight the differences in construction quality – portions of the later additions became dilapidated; whereas the original features retained their integrity.  We respected the physical presence of the additions but decided that they should be replaced with a referential addition that brings unity to the whole composition. \r\n\r\nThe design retains the integrity of the original building with very few changes to the original façade except those that are required for life safety and general repair to restore elements damaged by the storm. All new elements will draw upon the historic details, architecture and style to bring back the original building’s charm and provide a building that continues its historic use as a yacht club into the future.   \r\n'),
