(4455, 673, 'member_copy', 'Next morning I sent the butler to New York with a letter to Wolfshiem which asked for information and urged him to come out on the next train. Why''s that? Daisy''s leaving you. . You ought to have a church, George, for times like this. Each night he added to the pattern of his fancies until drowsiness closed down upon some vivid scene with an oblivious embrace. He took off his glasses and wiped them again outside and in. But Wilson stood there a long time, his face close to the window pane, nodding into the twilight. About Gatsby! No, I haven''t. In its deep gloom we sat down side by side on a wicker settee.\r\n\r\nOf theatrical people there were Gus Waize and Horace O''Donavan and Lester Meyer and George Duckweed and Francis Bull. I looked around. I''m all out of practice, you see. It was on that slender riotous island which extends itself due east of New York and where there are, among other natural curiosities, two unusual formations of land. He pointed out every detail to me eagerly. I know somebody there. Are you in love with me, she said low in my ear. She walked close to Gatsby, touching his coat with her hand. Oh, my! she gasped. I noticed that she wore her evening dress, all her dresses, like sports clothes—there was a jauntiness about her movements as if she had first learned to walk upon golf courses on clean, crisp mornings. ''All right,'' says Rosy and begins to get up and I pulled him down in his chair. It was a random shot, and yet the reporter''s instinct was right. No, said Gatsby, shaking his head. I''m p-paralyzed with happiness. It was a halt, too, in my association with his affairs. She''s got my hair and shape of the face. Ask Myrtle, said Tom, breaking into a short shout of laughter as Mrs. Wilson entered with a tray. She was in the middle thirties, and faintly stout, but she carried her surplus flesh sensuously as some women can. It had seemed as close as a star to the moon.\r\n\r\nMyrtle Wilson''s body wrapped in a blanket and then in another blanket as though she suffered from a chill in the hot night lay on a work table by the wall and Tom, with his back to us, was bending over it, motionless. I''m much obliged but I couldn''t take on any more work. It''ll show you how I''ve gotten to feel about—things. Come in. You may think that''s sentimental but I mean it—to the bitter end. It''s a swell suite, whispered Jordan respectfully and every one laughed. For a moment I suspected that he was pulling my leg but a glance at him convinced me otherwise.'),
