(4543, 680, 'member_copy', 'Next morning I sent the butler to New York with a letter to Wolfshiem which asked for information and urged him to come out on the next train. Why''s that? Daisy''s leaving you. You ought to have a church, George, for times like this. Each night he added to the pattern of his fancies until drowsiness closed down upon some vivid scene with an oblivious embrace. He took off his glasses and wiped them again outside and in. But Wilson stood there a long time, his face close to the window pane, nodding into the twilight. About Gatsby! No, I haven''t. In its deep gloom we sat down side by side on a wicker settee.\r\n\r\nOf theatrical people there were Gus Waize and Horace O''Donavan and Lester Meyer and George Duckweed and Francis Bull. I looked around. I''m all out of practice, you see. It was on that slender riotous island which extends itself due east of New York and where there are, among other natural curiosities, two unusual formations of land. He pointed out every detail to me eagerly. I know somebody there. Are you in love with me, she said low in my ear. \r\n\r\nMyrtle Wilson''s body wrapped in a blanket and then in another blanket as though she suffered from a chill in the hot night lay on a work table by the wall and Tom, with his back to us, was bending over it, motionless. I''m much obliged but I couldn''t take on any more work. It''ll show you how I''ve gotten to feel about—things. Come in. You may think that''s sentimental but I mean it—to the bitter end. It''s a swell suite, whispered Jordan respectfully and every one laughed. For a moment I suspected that he was pulling my leg but a glance at him convinced me otherwise.'),
