(5304, 804, 'project_description', 'Platt Byard Dovell White was the architect for the full restoration of the 1900 Landmark Courtroom of the First Department of the Appellate Division of the Supreme Court of the State of New York. The project began with an interior restoration, and was followed by the full exterior restoration.\r\n\r\nThe courthouse is possibly the finest integration of architecture and the decorative arts achieved in America in the 19th Century.  Intelligently conceived, scaled and laid out by the architect James Brown Lord and enriched by fine materials, fixtures and furnishings and an astonishing program of mural art brought together under the arbitration of John LaFarge, the Courtroom arranges around its remarkable glass dome an exceptionally thoughtful and inspiring context for some of the State’s most important juridical work.\r\n\r\nMajor work was done to the landmark interior to remove unsympathetic 1950’s renovations.  Replacement light fixtures were removed and replaced with replicas of the originals, including glass beaded chandeliers and cast bronze wall sconces.  The original center oculus of the Maitland Armstrong stained glass ceiling dome was replicated using historic photos of the courtroom.  Marble wall panels were cleaned and restored.  Original Herter Brothers wood furniture was restored and reupholstered in leather.  The centerpiece judge’s bench and reredos was restored, and the long-missing carved wood shell was replicated.  Custom broadloom was designed in a small-scale pattern to complement the scale of the room’s ornamentation, replacing the existing solid-color carpeting.\r\n\r\nExterior work included restoration of all façades and the sculpture groupings on the building.  The marble façades were cleaned, re-pointed and repaired with new stone dutchmen.  Aluminum replacement windows were replaced with new mahogany wood windows to match the original window configurations.\r\n\r\nThe sculptures were cleaned and consolidated to help retain as much original stone as possible.  Previously installed unsympathetic dutchmen were replaced with the same marble originally used.  Historic photos were used as the basis for the new carvings of arms, legs and faces for the sculptures. '),
