(5867, 956, 'project_description', 'The project involved a major renovation of Vassar College’s Van Ingen Art Library, an innovative work of late 1930’s architecture, designed specifically to support a particularly important part of Vassar’s curriculum.\r\n\r\nA key decision was made early by the faculty, library staff, and Platt Byard Dovell White Architects to re-establish the original Modernist character of Van Ingen’s spaces, undoing almost seventy-five years of wear and changes, while simultaneously upgrading the library for maximum functionality in a contemporary academic setting.\r\n\r\nTo meet this challenge, the re-design of the library entailed a comprehensive study of its historic elements.  A laboratory analysis was carried out to determine the materials and colors originally used.  (There were at least thirteen different paint colors.)  New finishes and new lighting throughout were selected to recreate the spirit of the original design.  A new circulation desk and new stairs to the stack level were placed to facilitate movement within the library.  Spacious new study rooms were designed to attract student users.  The library was technologically re-equipped to support an increasingly computerized fine arts pedagogy.  Exposed piping and wiring were re-routed and concealed to restore a smooth, uninterrupted expanse of ceiling, providing an even distribution of light across the space.  An informal seating area and display space were added to encourage diverse uses of the facility.'),
