(7426, 1107, 'project_description', 'Platt Byard Dovell White Architects was hired to study and re-imagine the facilities of The Educational Alliance, a non-profit institution that has been serving the community of the Lower East Side of New York for over 110 years. While in generally sound condition, the existing facility suffers from the inefficient use of space, poor circulation paths, and obsolete building systems.\r\n \r\nPBDW worked closely with The Educational Alliance to address these issues and developed a design that significantly expands the program area, revives the architecture, modernizes the physical plant for the entire facility, and is phased so portions of the building may remain occupied during the work.\r\n \r\nCentral to the design is the adaptive reuse of 197 East Broadway. The project also includes the restoration of street-side facades with the installation of new, historically appropriate windows, a modified primary entrance on East Broadway, and the cleaning, repair, and repointing of the masonry, where needed.\r\n \r\nA majority of the program space will be devoted to early-childhood classrooms serving children up to age 5. A portion of the roof will be dedicated to a newly landscaped play terrace for the early-childhood program. The fourth floor will house the main administration offices for The Educational Alliance core staff as well as seminar rooms that will host adult and teen programs. The fifth floor is devoted to a new fitness center, open to the community, which includes fitness studios and locker rooms with showers. The sixth floor contains a new column-free multi-purpose community room surrounded on two sides by a roof terrace.'),
