(8163, 1216, 'project_description', 'Designed for Peter Cooper by Frederick Peterson in 1858, the original palazzo of the Foundation Building had an Italianate formality that fit Cooper’s idea of his institute as an instrument to honor and elevate its beneficiaries.\r\n\r\nThe institution had done its best to maintain the Building over the years, but the brownstone exterior increasingly came apart. A catastrophic “preservation” idea of the 1950’s and 60’s - to jackhammer the entire surface of the brownstone to remove anything that might fall off on someone’s head - accelerated the penetration of water into the stone and obscured the clarity of the original expression in a mush of worm-like hammer tracks.\r\n\r\nOur restoration returned the building to a semblance of the original honed flat brownstone. The facades were honed to flatten them, then tooled with fine-toothed chisels to smooth out the remaining divots from the previous repairs. Brownstone from the same quarry that supplied the original stone was used to replace badly deteriorated stones. Projecting architectural elements were recarved to approximate the original profiles lost over time. New stone was installed at the North Portico, where the weather had affected the building most severely.  The South Portico was completely rebuilt to replace stones buried beneath layers of patches and stucco.'),
