(8199, 1218, 'project_description', 'New York’s first pastoral cemetery and its first great work of landscape design, the 1838 Green-Wood Cemetery in Brooklyn established the pattern of open-air movement in an inviting and rewarding planned landscape later explored and developed in Central Park and its successors. Offering a superb landscape in a pastoral setting, Green-Wood became a major public destination and outdoor recreation resource. \r\n\r\nPlatt Byard Dovell White has collaborated with Green-Wood on several projects, first addressing the preservation of the imposing gothic revival Gate by Richard Upjohn and the renovation of Beaux-Arts Chapel by Warren and Wetmore. In response to a need to accommodate contemporary burial practices in a sensitive landscape, we are now collaborating with Green-Wood to explore two unexamined but important building types - the above-ground mausoleum and cremation garden - with a major addition to Green-Wood’s Hillside Mausoleum and a new Columbarium. Both buildings are designed to carry out the intentions of the historic landscape in an architecture worthy of Green-Wood’s extremely high standards of design.\r\n\r\nThe design of the Hillside Mausoleum addition brings Green-Wood’s “landscape” through the glass greenhouse enclosure, making the space an extension of the outdoors. The transparency of the envelope, the glass pyramids, and blocks of crypts at the top entry of the mausoleum integrate it with the surrounding monuments and landscape, cut into an extremely sharp sloping site.\r\n\r\nThe Columbarium is conceived as a garden pavilion organized within a semi-circular wood and glass structure, enclosing a central meditation space set in a 150-foot reflecting pool. \r\n\r\nFollowing the form of an existing hemicycle of urn burials and integrated with the circulation between Green-Wood’s great Gate and it renovated Chapel, the Columbarium expands the inventory of commemorative structures in Green-Wood’s extraordinary landscape making possible a new experience of space, light, water and flowers by its pool and under its vine-covered pergolas.'),
